{{nihongo|'''Zion Suzuki'''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifadata.com/documents/FU17WC/2019/pdf/FU17WC_2019_Squadlists.pdf |title=FIFA U-17 World Cup Brazil 2019: List of Players: Japan |publisher=FIFA |page=13 |date=31 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227222540/https://www.fifadata.com/documents/FU17WC/2019/pdf/FU17WC_2019_Squadlists.pdf |archive-date=27 December 2019}}</ref>|鈴木 彩艶|Suzuki Zaion|born 21 August 2002}} is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Serie A]] club [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]]. Born in the United States, he represents the [[Japan national football team|Japan national team]].

== Early life ==
Suzuki was born in [[Newark, New Jersey]], United States, to a [[Ghanaians|Ghanaian]] father and a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] mother.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/special/2020news/athletes/10/40.html|title=Profile of Zion Suzuki|access-date=10 August 2023|language=ja|archive-date=8 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230708130455/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/special/2020news/athletes/10/40.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=日本放送協会 |title=鈴木彩艶のプロフィール｜サッカー｜東京オリンピックパラリンピック |trans-title=Zion Suzuki's profile |url=https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/special/2020news/athletes/10/40.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230708130455/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/news/special/2020news/athletes/10/40.html |archive-date=8 July 2023 |access-date=7 July 2023 |website=www3.nhk.or.jp}}</ref> He was named after the [[List of biblical places|biblical location]] of [[Mount Zion]] near [[Jerusalem]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2017-07-18 |title=U-15世代の中学生GK鈴木彩艶がU-17代表で学びの一週間。「這い上がっていけるように」 |trans-title=U-15 goalkeeper Zion Suzuki spends a week learning with the U-17 national team: “So I can work my way up.” |url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?221311-221311-fl |access-date=2024-08-25 |website=ゲキサカ |language=ja}}</ref> Suzuki's family later moved to Japan, settling in [[Urawa, Saitama]], where he was raised.<ref>{{cite news |date=2023-08-06 |title=浦和ＧＫ鈴木彩艶、シントトロイデン移籍を発表「世界で闘ってきます」マンＵの獲得打診断り決断 |trans-title=Urawa goalkeeper Zion Suzuki announces transfer to Sint-Truiden: "I will compete on the world stage" — turns down approach from Man U before making decision. |url=https://hochi.news/articles/20230806-OHT1T51126.html?page=1 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231017133244/https://hochi.news/articles/20230806-OHT1T51126.html?page=1 |archive-date=17 October 2023 |access-date=13 October 2023 |work=Hochi Shimbun}}</ref>

== Club career ==

=== Urawa Red Diamonds ===
Suzuki's professional career began with Japanese club [[Urawa Red Diamonds]] when he was 16 years and five months old, making him the youngest player in the history of the club to sign a professional contract. Suzuki made his debut for the club on 2 March 2021 in the [[J.League Cup]] match against [[Shonan Bellmare]] where he kept a [[Shutout#Association football|clean sheet]]. His first appearance in the [[J1 League]] came on 9 May 2021 in a match against [[Vegalta Sendai]] where he kept a clean sheet in a 2–0 win.<ref name=":0" /> He would then go on to play in the next five consecutive league matches with main choice goalkeeper [[Shusaku Nishikawa]] dropped due to poor performances. He recorded four clean sheets in six matches for Urawa Reds. Suzuki won the [[J.League Cup#New Hero Award|New Hero Award]] of the [[2021 J.League Cup]] in his first season at the club.

Suzuki made his [[2022 AFC Champions League]] debut against [[Singapore]]an club [[Lion City Sailors FC|Lion City Sailors]] on 15 April 2022; however, he made a costly error after receiving a back pass from [[David Moberg Karlsson]] which resulted in an own goal. In the next match against [[China|Chinese]] side [[Shandong Taishan F.C.|Shandong Taishan]], he kept a clean sheet in a 5–0 win. Suzuki played in the club four group stage fixtures before being dropped in favour of the first choice goalkeeper, [[Shusaku Nishikawa]], in the run all the way to the [[2022 AFC Champions League final]]. Suzuki helped the club to win the [[2022 AFC Champions League]] trophy and the [[2022 Japanese Super Cup]].

=== Sint-Truiden ===
In August 2023, Suzuki was sent on loan from the Urawa Red Diamonds to [[Sint-Truidense V.V.|Sint-Truiden]], a team in the [[Belgian Pro League]]. He served as the understudy for fellow Japanese goalkeeper [[Daniel Schmidt (footballer)|Daniel Schmidt]] before he was named the starter.

On 1 February 2024, it was announced that Suzuki's loan with Sint-Truiden would be converted into a permanent transfer for the next season on 1 July 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.urawa-reds.co.jp/topteamtopics/208444/ |title=Announcement of permanent transfer of Zion Suzuki to Sint-Truiden VV |website=www.urawa-reds.co.jp |date=February 2024 |language=Japanese |access-date=1 February 2024 |publisher=Urawa Red Diamonds }}</ref>

=== Parma ===
On 15 July 2024, [[Serie A]] club [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]] announced the signing of Suzuki to a five-year contract. He became the second Japanese national team player to represent the club after [[Hidetoshi Nakata]], who joined the club in mid-2001.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Subiantoro |first=Paulinus Hardi |date=16 July 2024 |title=Resmi Gabung Parma, Zion Suzuki Jadi Pemain Jepang Kedua yang Main di Gialloblu. |trans-title=Officially joining Parma, Zion Suzuki becomes the second Japanese player to play for the Gialloblu. |url=https://soccer.indozone.id/news/984869627/resmi-gabung-parma-zion-suzuki-jadi-pemain-jepang-kedua-yang-main-di-gialloblu#google_vignette |access-date=19 December 2024 |website=Indozone |language=id}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Zion Suzuki is a Gialloblu |url=https://www.parmacalcio1913.com/en/main-news/zion-suzuki-e-gialloblu/ |date=15 July 2024 |access-date=20 July 2024 |publisher=Parma Calcio 1913}}</ref>

On 17 August 2024, he made his league debut against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], which ended in a 1–1 draw.<ref>{{cite news |title= Parma 1-1 Fiorentina: Match report and highlights |url= https://www.msn.com/en-xl/sports/football/parma-1-1-fiorentina-match-report-and-highlights/ar-AA1oYgTy |date=17 August 2024 |access-date=21 August 2024 |publisher=MSN}}</ref>

== International career ==
Suzuki has represented Japan at multiple levels in youth football. On 19 July 2022, he earned his first cap with [[Japan national football team|Japan's national team]], playing the full match against [[Hong Kong national football team|Hong Kong]] in the [[2022 EAFF E-1 Football Championship]], which his side won 6–0.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Z. Suzuki |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/zion-suzuki/502022/ |access-date=7 July 2023 |website=Soccerway |archive-date=7 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230707162733/https://my.soccerway.com/players/zion-suzuki/502022/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

He played in Japan's opening match of the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]], a 4–2 win against [[Vietnam national football team|Vietnam]]. He also played in their following 1–2 defeat to [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]], logging one save.

